To automatically generate a table of contents (ToC) in a LaTeX document, you employ the `\tableofcontents` command from the `book-class` functionality of functionality is available in LaTeX’s core. However, more fine-grained control and support for various document classes like `article`, `report`, and alike is achieved by utilizing the `\tableofcontents` functionality along with the `\label` and `\sectioning` commands from the `\part`, `\chapter`, `\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection`, `\paragraph`, and `\subparagraph` families. Here's a comprehensive example demonstrating this:

```latex
\documentclass[12pt,openright]{report} % or you might use 'article' or 'book' depending on your document structure

\begin{document}

\frontmatter
\pagenumbering{roman}
\tableofcontents % This command generates the ToC

\clearpage
\addcontentsline{toc}{frontmatter}{Abstract}
\chapter*{Abstract}

\clearpage
\addcontentsline{toc}{frontmatter}{Preface}
\chapter*{Preface}

\mainmatter
\setcounter{section}{0} % Reset section numbering

\chapter{Introduction}
\label{chap:introduction}
\section{Background}\label sec:bg}
\subsection{\label{sec:bg:related}Related Work}
\subsection{\label{sec:bg:problem}Problem Statement}
\section{\label{sec:introduction:methods}Methods}
\section{\label{sec:introduction:result}Results}
\section{\label{sec:introduction:conclusion}Conclusion}

\chapter{Methods}
\label{chap:methods}
\section{\label{sec:methods:data}Data}
\section{\label{sec:methods:model}Model}

\backmatter
\addcontentsline{toc}{backmatter}{References}
\bibliography{yourbibfile}

\addcontentsline{toc}{backmatter}{Appendix}
\appendix
\chapter{Additional Material}\label{chap:appendix}

\end{document}

Customizations:
- The `\documentclass` command defines the document type and its properties.
- `\tableofcontents` should be placed after setting up the front matter elements like title page, abstract, and preface.
- To include an item in the ToC without being numbered as a chapter (like Abstract, Preface), use `\chapter*`.
- The `\addcontentsline` command helps to manually add entries to the ToC. You should use this when necessary, such as adding items outside of standard sectioning commands like an abstract or bibliography.
- The `\setcounter{section}{0}` command resets section numbers when moving from front matter to main content.

This example illustrates how to generate a table of contents automatically in LaTeX for a report document structure. The same principles apply to article and book documents with slight modifications according to their inherent structures. Make sure to use correct sectioning commands (`\part`, `\chapter`, `\section`, etc.) and label them for proper referencing throughout your document. This will ensure a comprehensive and correctly formatted table of contents.

To draw a chessboard according to a given FEN notation in LaTeX, you'll require a dedicated package named `xskak` or alternatively a combination of `tikz` and some parsing of the FEN notation. Here’s a comprehensive solution that covers both approaches.

### Method with xskak Package
First, you need to install the `xskak` package if it’s not already available. This package is specifically designed for drawing chess boards and pieces according to FEN notation. Below is a complete LaTeX code that utilizes the `xskak` package:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[margin=2cm]{geometry}
\usepackage{helvet}
\renewfontfamily{\kbf}{\fontseries{l}\selectfont}% use bold font from Helvetica-like family
\usepackage{chessfnt}
\usepackage{xtab}
\usepackage{xskak}
\setupfichess

\begin{document}

\makeatletter
\boardname{Starting Position}
\mainline{
\rkqi{1.1}{wn}{b}{w}{r}{b}{q}{i}{k}{p}
rnrbqk1/ppppppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK1NR w - - 0 1
}

\begin{center}
\makebox[0pt]{\kbf{Name:}}\hspace{5mm}\chessboard
\end{center}

\end{document}
```

In this code:
- We set up the document structure with necessary packages and font configurations.
- The `\mainline{\rktqi...}` directive specifies the `\setupfichess` command, where you provide the given FEN string as the second argument.
- The `\boardname` command sets the title above the board.
- Finally, `\chessboard` actually prints the board according to the provided FEN.

### Method with Tikz
If you prefer using Tikz for more customization, here’s an alternative approach:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[margin=2cm]{geometry}
\usepackage{helvet}
\renewfontfamily{\kbf}{\fontseries{l}\selectfont}% use bold font from Helvetica-like family
\usepackage{tikz}

\newcommand{\chesssquare}[3]{%
  \draw[very thin] (#1-\straft,#2-.5) rectangle (#1-.5+\straft,#2+.5);
  \if#3b%
    \if#4w%
      \filldraw[fill=white] (#1-.5+\straft,#2+.5) rectangle (#1+.5-\straft,#2-.5);
      \node[font=\kbf] at (#1,-#2+.25) {\small \pgfkeysvalueof{/pgf/square piece/#4}};
    \else
      \filldraw[fill=black!50] (#1-.5+\straft,#2+.5) rectangle (#1+.5-\straft,#2-.5);
      \node[font=\kbf] at (#1,-#2+.25) {\small \pgfkeysvalueof{/pgf/square piece/#4}};
    \fi
  \fi
}

\pgfkeys{/pgf/square piece/.is family,
  /pgf/square piece/.going aliases,
  r/.initial=r,
  n/.initial=n,
  b/.initial=b,
  q/.initial=q,
  k/.initial=k,
  p/.initial=p,
  R/.initial=R,
  N/.initial=N,
  B/.initial=B,
  Q/.initial=Q,
  K/.initial=K,
  P/.initial=P}

\newcommand{\drawchessboard}[1]{%
  \edef\FEN{{#1}}
  \foreach \x in {1,...,8} {
    \foreach \y in {7,...,1} {
      \edef\squarepiece{}
      \foreach \piece [count=\pi from 0] in \extractpiecesfromFEN{\FEN}{\y-8+\x} {
        \pgfmathtruncate{\pi div 6}=\xi,
        \pgfmathtruncate{\pi-6*\xi}=pietype;
        \edef\squarepiece{#squarepiece\b\xi b#squarepiece,\ifcase\piteype
          b{return b}\or n{return N}\or r{return R}\or r{return R}\or q{return Q}\or k{return K}\or p{return P}\fi}
        }
        \chesssquare{\x}{\y}{#1=\squarepiece=={}}
      }
      \draw[dashed] (\x-.5,0.5) -- (\x-.5,-7.5);
    }
    \draw[dashed] (0.5,-7.5) -- (8-.5,-7.5);
  }
  \foreach \y in {0,...,7} {
    \draw[dashed] (0.5,\y-.5) node[below] {\small 8-\y} -- (8-.5,\y-.5);
  }
}

\begin{document}

\begin{center}
  \setlength{\straft}{1cm}
  \drawchessboard{rnrbqk1/ppppppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK1NR w - - 0 1}
  \end{center}

\end{document}
```

In this Tikz-based approach:
- We define a command `\chesssquare` to draw a single square with its contents.
- A `pgfkeys` family defines aliases for chess pieces.
- The `\drawchessboard` command parses the FEN string and draws each square accordingly.
- It includes a loop to draw horizontal and vertical lines to form the chess grid.

Both examples above will render a chessboard according to the given FEN string `rnrbqk1/ppppppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK1NR w - - 0 1`, representing the starting position of a chess game.

You can choose either approach based on your specific requirements and preferences regarding customization and complexity. The `xskak` package provides a simpler and more straightforward solution for drawing chessboards from FEN strings, while the Tikz-based approach offers more flexibility in terms of customizations and board design.

